## P2 — Add identity and network-exposure controls before multi-user deployment

- **Who:** EvalForge API/dashboard owner; repository
  `/Users/fortunevieyra/Documents/Github/ai-projects/llm-evaluation-dashboard`.
- **What:** The application has no authentication, authorization, tenant boundary, TLS ingress,
  user-scoped data model, or abuse/rate-limit layer.
- **How discovered:** Security-model review, Compose proof, and the explicit single-user boundary in
  README, architecture, operations, and `docs/security.md`.
- **Where:** `src/evalforge/api/app.py`, all `src/evalforge/api/routes/*.py`,
  `src/evalforge/models.py`, `src/evalforge/repositories.py`, dashboard API state/client,
  `compose.yaml`, and security/operations documentation.
- **When:** Before binding beyond loopback, placing the app behind a public ingress, sharing one
  database between users, or accepting proprietary benchmarks from multiple identities.
- **Detailed description:** Current resource IDs are global and every API consumer can read or
  mutate every resource. Trusted-host, CORS, security headers, body bounds, and server-side secrets
  reduce local risk but are not identity controls. Network exposure without a principal/tenant
  model would make prompts, outputs, references, request IDs, and costs cross-user readable.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - Every request has an authenticated principal and explicit authorization decision.
  - Dataset, prompt, model, run, result, export, comparison, and analytics queries are tenant-scoped.
  - Anonymous, cross-tenant, stale-session, and role-transition tests fail closed.
  - TLS termination, secret management, rate limits, audit events, and retention are documented and
    verified at the deployed ingress.
  - Dashboard identity state cannot reuse cached data across sign-in/sign-out or tenant changes.
- **Definition of done:** Migrations, API contracts, UI states, exports, metrics, seed fixtures, and
  operational runbooks all carry identity scope; Playwright proves anonymous/authenticated/admin
  journeys; API tests prove object-level authorization; hosted readback verifies the deployed
  policy; the threat model is updated.
- **Reason the issue exists:** The requested portfolio scope prioritized a complete, safe,
  deterministic local evaluator. Adding superficial auth without tenant-scoped persistence would
  create a more dangerous false sense of safety, so network exposure was deliberately deferred.
- **Priority:** P2.
- **Why this priority:** It does not affect loopback single-user correctness, but it is a hard blocker
  for any public or shared deployment.
- **Regression prevention:** Central authorization dependencies, tenant keys in uniqueness/cache
  boundaries, denial-first fixtures, immutable audit events, and cross-identity regression tests.
- **Testing:** Pytest for API/repository authorization; Playwright for login, logout, role, cache,
  deep-link, and cross-tenant E2E. Cypress is not applicable because this is not a React repository.
- **Audit policies:** identity-context regression, route/API contract mapping, state-readback
  persistence, validation-proof selection, security review, and deploy-hazard review.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Encrypt or otherwise protect database/export data at rest according to the deployment threat
    model.
  - Decide whether provider credentials are deployment-wide or tenant-specific before schema work.
  - Define deletion/retention behavior without weakening immutable evaluation provenance.

## P3 — Eliminate the cold direct-deep-link Streamlit bootstrap overlay

- **Who:** Streamlit dashboard owner.
- **What:** A first request to a dynamic subroute such as `/evaluate` on a cold Streamlit process
  can show Streamlit's framework “Page not found” overlay while still rendering the selected page.
- **How discovered:** Root-agent browser validation first navigated directly to
  `http://127.0.0.1:8501/evaluate`; DOM, screenshot, and console all showed the overlay/error. A
  fresh session entering at `/` and clicking the visible navigation was clean.
- **Where:** `src/evalforge/dashboard/app.py`, `tests/e2e/test_dashboard_smoke.py`,
  `docs/operations.md`, and potentially the pinned Streamlit version/configuration.
- **When:** Only on a cold process before the initial session registers pages and the user enters by
  a subroute URL. Root-first navigation and warmed route changes are unaffected.
- **Detailed description:** `st.navigation` registers function-backed pages during application
  execution. The Streamlit frontend can evaluate the requested path before that registration exists,
  emit its own overlay/error, then run the correct page. The current supported contract starts at
  root and navigates through the menu; the E2E test intentionally models that path.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - A newly started server accepts direct `/evaluate`, `/runs`, `/compare`, `/assets`, and
    `/settings` requests without an overlay or console error.
  - The correct route is active and browser back/forward behavior remains correct.
  - Desktop/mobile layout and accessibility remain unchanged.
- **Definition of done:** Implement a proven static-page, router, or framework-upgrade solution;
  add a Playwright cold-server deep-link matrix; record clean DOM/screenshot/console evidence; remove
  the root-first limitation from docs only after proof.
- **Reason the issue exists:** It is a Streamlit dynamic-route bootstrap timing behavior, not an API
  or persisted-state failure.
- **Priority:** P3.
- **Why this priority:** The documented root workflow is fully functional and browser-clean; the
  issue affects bookmarks/cold deep links rather than evaluation correctness or data safety.
- **Regression prevention:** Keep one cold-server direct-link Playwright test per route and require
  console-error checks.
- **Testing:** Playwright E2E only for route/bootstrap behavior; Streamlit AppTest remains suitable
  for page/component logic.
- **Audit policies:** frontend proof, route/API contract mapping, validation-proof selection, and
  design-system consistency.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Do not hide or auto-dismiss the overlay as a substitute for fixing route registration.
  - Preserve visible, keyboard-accessible navigation and current URLs.
  - Recheck behavior on every Streamlit upgrade.

## P3 — Obtain external PostgreSQL and GitHub Actions evidence

- **Who:** CI/release/operations owner.
- **What:** PostgreSQL support and a service-backed CI job are configured, but this no-remote local
  repository has no actual GitHub Actions run or retained PostgreSQL job URL.
- **How discovered:** Repository/remote inspection returned no Git remote; validation therefore used
  SQLite, isolated wheel install, and local Docker Compose.
- **Where:** `.github/workflows/ci.yml`, `src/evalforge/database.py`,
  `src/evalforge/migrations/**`, `docs/operations.md`, and a future Git remote.
- **When:** After publishing the repository or before claiming PostgreSQL/CI proof as externally
  verified.
- **Detailed description:** The workflow provisions PostgreSQL, installs the explicit
  `postgresql+psycopg` extra, migrates, seeds, and runs doctor. Contract tests validate the
  configuration, but only an executed remote job proves runner/service behavior.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - A remote Actions run is green for lint, types, security, core coverage, PostgreSQL smoke, build,
    and Playwright E2E.
  - PostgreSQL reaches migration 0002, seeds 2/2/3 fixtures, reports ready, and leaves no schema diff.
  - The run URL, commit SHA, and job logs are recorded without secrets.
- **Definition of done:** Add a remote, push the two local commits, execute CI, remediate any
  runner-only failures, and update the completion record with immutable run links and exact SHA.
- **Reason the issue exists:** The user requested a new local project; no publication destination or
  authority to create/push a remote was provided.
- **Priority:** P3.
- **Why this priority:** SQLite satisfies the required database choice and is deeply proven;
  PostgreSQL is an optional scale path, and CI configuration is already present.
- **Regression prevention:** Keep migration/schema-diff tests, explicit driver URL validation,
  service readiness checks, and branch-protected required jobs after publication.
- **Testing:** Pytest integration against PostgreSQL plus Playwright E2E in the separate job.
- **Audit policies:** validation-proof selection, route/API contract mapping, state-readback
  persistence, preexisting-failure triage, and deploy-automation hazards.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Do not claim horizontal workers merely because PostgreSQL connects.
  - Add durable queue/lease semantics and locking tests before increasing worker count.
  - Keep credentials in Actions secrets and out of logs/artifacts.

## P3 — Calibrate optional paid-provider and judge metrics before using them as release gates

- **Who:** Evaluation/provider owner.
- **What:** OpenAI and compatible-provider contracts are implemented and mocked, but no paid live
  call, human-calibrated threshold study, RAGAS/DeepEval plugin, LangSmith, or W&B integration was
  executed.
- **How discovered:** Proof-boundary audit and the user's stack list, where tracking frameworks were
  optional. Real calls remained disabled throughout validation.
- **Where:** `src/evalforge/evaluation/adapters/openai_compatible.py`,
  `src/evalforge/evaluation/metrics.py`, run snapshots/exports, and evaluation-methodology docs.
- **When:** Before treating heuristic scores as production release gates or enabling a real provider
  in a shared environment.
- **Detailed description:** Deterministic lexical/evidence metrics are transparent regression
  signals, not factual truth. A judge/plugin must persist model, API mode, rubric bytes/hash, schema,
  version, calibration set, applicability, request ID, usage, and cost without replacing the offline
  core.
- **Acceptance criteria:**
  - A small explicitly authorized live run preserves request IDs, usage, latency, cost source, and
    provider errors without secret leakage.
  - Human-reviewed calibration reports precision/recall or agreement at selected thresholds.
  - Any plugin/judge returns not-applicable for missing prerequisites and is versioned in snapshots.
  - Paid execution retains preflight and both consent gates.
- **Definition of done:** Implement the optional adapter/metric, add mocked contract tests, run a
  bounded authorized provider proof, produce a calibration artifact, and document exact limitations.
- **Reason the issue exists:** Live spend and external data transmission require credentials and
  explicit authority; optional tracking/evaluator services were not required for the complete
  offline product.
- **Priority:** P3.
- **Why this priority:** The deterministic evaluator already fulfills the requested dashboard; this
  work improves external validity rather than fixing a local correctness defect.
- **Regression prevention:** Offline-by-default CI, marked live tests, immutable rubric/provider
  versions, cost caps, and calibration-set versioning.
- **Testing:** Mocked unit/integration tests by default; explicitly marked bounded live tests; human
  calibration review; Playwright only for disclosure/consent UI.
- **Audit policies:** payment/cost safety, route/API contract mapping, state-readback persistence,
  validation-proof selection, and security/privacy review.
- **Other considerations:**
  - Never pass references into candidate prompts.
  - Never silently fall back between Responses and Chat Completions.
  - Never report unknown price as zero or demo telemetry as live-provider telemetry.

